===Nightlife===
{{Original research|date=June 2008}}{{Refimprove|date=June 2008}}
[[File:Sheas.jpg|thumb|right|Shea's Performing Arts Center]]
[[Last call (bar term)|Last call]] is at 4&nbsp;am in Buffalo,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.visitbuffaloniagara.com/things-to-do/nightlife/|title=Things to Do|publisher=Visitbuffalo.com}}, Retrieved 2013-5-31.</ref> rather than 2&nbsp;am as in most other areas of the U.S. This is often attributed {{by whom|date=June 2013}} to the historically high density of industrial facilities and the demand of second and third [[shift work|shift]] patrons. It is also because New York law allows bars to be open until 4&nbsp;am (However, local municipalities can override it to an earlier time.)

Several distinct and [[Nightlife (activity)|nightlife]] districts have grown around clusters of bars and nightclubs in the city. The most visible nightlife district is West Chippewa Street,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.westchippewa.com/ |title=Buffalo Bills, Buffalo Sabres, Buffalo NightLife, chippewa street, west chippewa street, Chippewa Street, West Chippewa Street |publisher=Westchippewa.com |date= }}</ref> located between Main Street and South Elmwood Avenue.  [[Allentown, Buffalo, New York|Allentown]] is a several minute walk north to Allen Street. Allen Street near Main Street houses several bars, while Allen near Elmwood has many bars that feature live music. Continuing up Elmwood Avenue from Allentown is the Elmwood Strip, which runs about two miles (3&nbsp;km) to [[Buffalo State College]]. This strip has numerous small boutiques and restaurants, with few large corporate establishments.

===Public festivals===
Like many large cities, numerous festivals have become part of the city's culture and tradition. Though most of the festivals occur during the summer months, the city has recently pushed efforts to have winter festivals as well in an effort to capitalize on the region's snowy reputation.

[[File:Buffalo maritime center launch.JPG|thumb|right|225px|Maritime Center boat launch along the [[Commercial Slip]].]]

====Summer festivals====
* [[Allentown Art Festival]] – Largest festival of the year on the second weekend of June in the city's Allentown neighborhood.
* [[Taste of Buffalo]] – One of the largest outdoor food festivals in the country.
* [http://www.buffalogreekfestival.org Buffalo Greek Festival]
* [http://www.buffaloitalianfestival.com/ Italian Festival]
* [http://dozynki.corpuschristibuffalo.org/ Dożynki Polish Harvest Festival]
* [[National Buffalo Wing Festival]]
* [http://www.askbhsc.org/Home/BuffaloBrewFest/ Buffalo Brewfest]
* [http://www.curtainupbuffalo.com/ Curtain Up!] – Marks the beginning of the Buffalo theater season.
* [[Thursday at the Square]] – Weekly outdoor summer concert series on Thursday evenings during the summer and fall
*[http://buffaloredcross.org/bash.php  The BASH]- A military themed fundraiser in which all proceeds go towards vital disaster preparedness education and response in Western New York communities.
* Elmwood Avenue Festival of the Arts<ref>{{cite web|url=http://eafa.techriver.net/ |title=Welcome to the 2011 Elmwood Avenue Festival of the Arts! |publisher=Eafa.techriver.net |date= }}</ref>
* [[Juneteenth|Juneteenth Festival]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.juneteenthofbuffalo.com/ |title=Juneteenth Buffalo |publisher=Juneteenthofbuffalo.com |date= }}</ref> is an annual celebration of the freedom of slaves.

====Winter festivals====
* Buffalo Powder Keg Festival<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.visitbuffaloniagara.com/includes/events/?action=displayDetail&eventId=61215|title=Buffalo Winterfest & Powder Keg Festival|publisher=Visit Buffalo Niagra.com}}, Retrieved 2013-5-31.</ref>
* Labatt Blue Pond Hockey<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.labattbluepondhockey.com/|title=Home|publisher= Labatt Blue Pond Hockey}}, Retrieved 2013-5-31.</ref>
* Saint Patrick's Day Parade<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.buffalostpatricksdayparade.com/|title=Home|publisher=Buffalo St. Patricks Day Parade.com}}, Retrieved 2013-5-31.</ref>
* [http://dyngusdaybuffalo.com/ Dyngus Day Buffalo]

===Other points of interest===
[[File:U.S.S. Little Rock, Buffalo New York - anothersaab.jpg|thumb|right|250px|[[USS Little Rock (CL-92)]] at the [[Buffalo and Erie County Naval & Military Park]]]]
* [[Edward M. Cotter (fireboat)|Edward M. Cotter fireboat]]&nbsp;– Considered to be the world's oldest active [[fireboat]] and is a United States [[National Historic Landmark]]
* [[Buffalo and Erie County Botanical Gardens]]
* [[Buffalo and Erie County Historical Society]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bechs.org/ |title=The Buffalo & Erie County Historical Society Buffalo New York |publisher=Bechs.org |date= }}</ref>
* [[Buffalo Museum of Science]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sciencebuff.org/ |title=Buffalo Museum of Science – Home |publisher=Sciencebuff.org |date= }}</ref>
* [[Buffalo Zoo]]&nbsp;– The third oldest zoo in the United States established in 1875
* [[Forest Lawn Cemetery (Buffalo)|Forest Lawn Cemetery]]
* "Mark Twain Room" at the Central Branch of the [[Buffalo and Erie County Public Library]].<ref>[http://www.buffalolib.org/libraries/collections/index.asp?sec=twain Buffalo & Erie County Public Library: Collections of Special Interest]{{dead link|date=August 2013}}</ref> Contains the original manuscript of ''[[Adventures of Huckleberry Finn|Huckleberry Finn]]''
* [[USS Little Rock (CG-4)]] in [[Buffalo and Erie County Naval & Military Park]]
* The [[Anchor Bar]]&nbsp;– birthplace of the [[Buffalo wing]] or the chicken wing as it is commonly called in the region
* [[Lafayette Square, Buffalo|Lafayette Square]]
* Penn Dixie Paleontological and Outdoor Education Center

==Transportation==
[[File:Peace Bridge - at Moonrise.jpg|thumb|right|The [[Peace Bridge]] connecting Buffalo to Fort Erie, Canada]]

===Airport===
Buffalo is served by the [[Buffalo Niagara International Airport]], located in [[Cheektowaga]]. The airport, recently re-constructed, serves over 5 million passengers a year and is still growing. Buffalo Niagara International Airport ranks among the five cheapest airports from which to fly in the country, according to the U.S. Bureau of Transportation Statistics. The average round trip flight cost is $295.58.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.buffaloniagara.org/files/content/Industry/Back_Office.pdf|title=Buffalo Niagara Region Shared Services Opportunities|publisher=Buffaloniagra.org}}, Retrieved 2013-5-31.</ref> In the last few years there has been a surge in Canadians flying out of Buffalo, mainly due to much cheaper tax and airline surcharges, as compared with Canadian airports and the ability to fly on some US based discount carriers not available in Canada (for example, [[JetBlue Airways]] and [[Southwest Airlines]]). As of 2006, plans are in the works by U.S. Senator [[Charles Schumer]] to make the under-used [[Niagara Falls International Airport]] into an international cargo hub for New York and [[Toronto]], as well as Canada as a whole.<ref>{{cite news|title=Niagara airport pushed as trade hub; Schumer joins effort to bring global cargo|author=Bill Michelmore|work=Buffalo News|page=B1|date=June 26, 2006}}</ref>
[[File:Main Court Building, Buffalo.JPG|right|thumb|The [[Buffalo Metro Rail|Metro Rail]] in downtown]]

===Public transit===
[[File:NFTAMetroRail.jpg|thumb|right|An outbound NFTA Metro Rail train pulls into Fountain Plaza Station]]
The [[Niagara Frontier Transportation Authority]] (NFTA) operates Buffalo Niagara International Airport and [[Niagara Falls International Airport]], and the [[public transport|public transit]] system throughout the Buffalo area. The [[NFTA]] operates bus lines throughout the city and suburbs, as well as the [[Buffalo Metro Rail|Metro Rail]] transit system in the city.

The Buffalo Metro Rail is a {{convert|6.4|mi|km}} long, single line [[light rail]] system that extends from [[Erie Canal Harbor]] in downtown Buffalo to the [[University Heights, Buffalo, New York|University Heights]] district (specifically, the South Campus of [[University at Buffalo, The State University of New York|University at Buffalo]]) in the northeastern part of the city. The downtown section of the line runs above ground and is free of charge to passengers. North of Theater Station, at the northern end of downtown, the line moves underground, remaining underground until it reaches the northern terminus of the line at University Heights. Passengers pay a fare to ride this section of the rail.

A new NFTA project is underway, often called "Cars on Main Street", that will substantially revise the downtown portion of the Metro Rail. It will allow vehicular traffic and Metro Rail cars to share Main St. in a manner similar to that of the trolleys of [[Muni Metro|San Francisco]]. The design includes new stations and pedestrian-friendly improvements. The first phase of the project, restoring two way traffic on Main Street between Edward and West Tupper, was completed in 2009. When the entire project is complete in the next few years, the downtown portion of Main St. will be re-opened to vehicular traffic for the first time in almost 30 years.{{Citation needed|date=May 2010}}

===Intercity rail===
Two train stations, [[Buffalo-Depew (Amtrak station)|Buffalo-Depew]] and [[Buffalo-Exchange Street Station|Buffalo-Exchange Street]] serve the city and are operated by [[Amtrak]]. Historically the city was a major stop on through routes between Chicago and New York City through the lower Ontario peninsula.<ref name=drury>{{cite book | last = Drury | first = George H. | authorlink =  | coauthors = | title = The Historical Guide to North American Railroads: Histories, Figures, and Features of more than 160 Railroads Abandoned or Merged since 1930 | publisher = Kalmbach Publishing | year = 1994 | location = [[Waukesha, Wisconsin]] | pages = 91, 229–231| doi = | id = | isbn = 0-89024-072-8}}</ref> Additionally, the [[Pennsylvania Railroad]] ran trains between Buffalo and [[Washington, D.C.]] on the [[Buffalo Line]] through central [[Pennsylvania]].<ref>1957 Pennsylvania Railroad schedules reprinted at http://www.therailwire.net/forum/index.php?topic=17913.15</ref>

Freight service for Buffalo is served by [[CSX Transportation]] and [[Norfolk Southern]] (NS), as well as [[Canadian National]] (CN) and [[Canadian Pacific]] (CP) railroads from across the Border. The area has 4 large rail yards: Frontier (CSX), Bison (NS), SK (NS / CP) and Buffalo Creek (NS / CSX). A large amount of hazardous cargo also crosses through the Buffalo area, such as liquid [[propane]] and [[anhydrous ammonia]].

===Waterways===
Buffalo is at the eastern end of one of the [[Great Lakes]], [[Lake Erie]], which boasts the greatest variety of freshwater sportfish in the country. The Lake serves as a playground for numerous personal yachts, sailboats, power boats and watercraft. The city has an extensive [[breakwall]] system protecting its inner and outer Lake Erie [[harbor]]s, which are maintained at commercial navigation depths for [[Great Lakes]] freighters.

A Lake Erie tributary that flows through south Buffalo is the [[Buffalo River (New York)|Buffalo River]], for which the city is named. Buffalo is historically linked to the fabled [[Erie Canal]], which ends where the [[Black Rock Channel]] enters [[Lake Erie]]. When the Canal was dedicated in 1825, its conceiver, New York State governor [[DeWitt Clinton]] took waters from Lake Erie at Buffalo's Western Terminus of the Canal (now the [[Commercial Slip]]). He sailed to New York City on the Canal packet ''[[Seneca Chief]]'', which later returned to Buffalo with Atlantic Ocean water. The seawater was poured into the Lake by Judge and future Buffalo Mayor [[Samuel Wilkeson]]. Once a major route for passengers and cargo, the Erie Canal played a primary role in opening up the American West to settlers from the east.  The Canal is now used primarily for pleasure craft and some light local freight, and in Buffalo it bypasses the swift upper reach of the [[Niagara River]]. A tributary of the Niagara River is [[Scajaquada Creek]], which flows though Buffalo, via the [[Frederick Law Olmsted]]-designed Delaware Lake and Park.

===National and state highway access===
[[File:Buffalo area road network map.png|thumb|right|Major highways that serve the Greater Buffalo area]]
* [[File:I-90.svg|20px]] [[File:NYS Thruway Sign.svg|20px]] [[Interstate 90]] ([[New York State Thruway]])
* [[File:I-190.svg|20px]] [[File:NYS Thruway Sign.svg|20px]] [[Interstate 190 (New York)|Interstate 190]], New York State Thruway's Niagara Section, travels from I-90 in southwest Cheektowaga to Niagara River in Lewiston. The only tolled portion is now the bridges connecting Grand Island to Niagara Falls (north), and Buffalo (south).
* [[File:I-290 (NY).svg|20px]] [[Interstate 290 (New York)]], Youngmann Memorial Highway, connects Buffalo with its northern suburbs of Amherst and Tonawanda, and provides a route to Niagara Falls that bypasses the city of Buffalo.
* [[File:I-990.svg|20px]] [[Interstate 990]], short interstate highway located entirely in the town of Amherst, NY.
* [[File:US 62.svg|20px]] [[US 62|U.S. Route 62, Bailey Ave and South Park Ave.]]
